{"body": "Run this (https://gist.github.com/2656171) on 100,000 key hash, I get results like below..\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n```\r\nstringify_keys\r\nRehearsal ---------------------------------------------------\r\nblock:            0.150000   0.010000   0.160000 (  0.166755)\r\nmethod send:      0.170000   0.010000   0.180000 (  0.177955)\r\nold way:          0.160000   0.010000   0.170000 (  0.162745)\r\n------------------------------------------ total: 0.510000sec\r\n\r\n                      user     system      total        real\r\nblock:            0.150000   0.000000   0.150000 (  0.153099)\r\nmethod send:      0.130000   0.000000   0.130000 (  0.133284)\r\nold way:          0.140000   0.000000   0.140000 (  0.144368)\r\n\r\n\r\nstringify_keys!\r\nRehearsal ---------------------------------------------------\r\nblock:            0.180000   0.000000   0.180000 (  0.177110)\r\nmethod send:      0.160000   0.000000   0.160000 (  0.160986)\r\nold way:          0.130000   0.010000   0.140000 (  0.136390)\r\n------------------------------------------ total: 0.480000sec\r\n\r\n                      user     system      total        real\r\nblock:            0.130000   0.000000   0.130000 (  0.130163)\r\nmethod send:      0.140000   0.000000   0.140000 (  0.142810)\r\nold way:          0.120000   0.000000   0.120000 (  0.124379)\r\n```\r\n\r\nThoughts?\r\n\r\nStyle and functionality wise, I think I prefer passing a block instead of a method name...I think it provides a little more flexibility for not much cost. Would allow for things hash.transform_keys{ |key| key.camelcase(:lower) }.", "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rails/rails/issues/comments/5638102", "created_at": "2012-05-10T22:10:38Z", "html_url": "https://github.com/rails/rails/pull/6259#issuecomment-5638102", "updated_at": "2012-05-10T22:10:38Z", "repo": "rails", "issue_id": 6259, "user": {"following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/markmcspadden/following{/other_user}", "events_url": "https://api.github.com/